    caption: [Copulation in insects (see also Figures 21.2B and 21.7B). A, *Omura congrua* (order Orthoptera) are a kind of grasshopper found in Brazil. B, Bluet damselflies, *Enallagma* sp. (order Odonata), are common throughout North America. Here, a male still grasps a female after copulation. The female (white abdomen) lays eggs in the water.],
    path: "../fig/fig-2025-12-01-16-05-31.png"
  ),
  "figure-21-22": (
    caption: [Complete (holometabolous) metamorphosis in a butterfly, *Danaus plexippus*. Eggs hatch to produce first of several larval instars. Last larval instar molts to become a pupa. Adult emerges at pupal molt.],
    path: "../fig/fig-2025-12-01-16-05-59.png"
  ),
  "figure-21-23": (
    caption: [A, Mosquito *Culex* (order Diptera) lays her eggs in small packets or rafts on the surface of standing or slowly moving water. B, Mosquito larvae are the familiar wrigglers of ponds and ditches. To breathe, they hang head down, with respiratory tubes projecting through the surface film of water. Motion of vibratile tufts of fine hairs on the head brings a constant supply of food to these filter feeders.],
    path: "../fig/fig-2025-12-01-16-06-14.png"
  ),
  "figure-21-24": (
    caption: [A, Ecdysis in a cicada, *Tibicen davisi* (order Hemiptera). The old cuticle splits along a dorsal midline as a result of increased blood pressure and of air forced into the thorax by muscle contraction. The emerging insect is pale, and its new cuticle is soft. The wings will be expanded by blood pumped into veins, and the insect enlarges by taking in air. B, An adult *Tibicen davisi*.],
    path: "../fig/fig-2025-12-01-16-06-48.png"
  ),
